{"source_key":"sha256-3a5b5d96dd2ea5b15c26eb39a6a02f34","record_index":10,"record_hash":"sha256:15a3d1f0849006fefc6b4afa5c1a5c9701816b11e41eb7d8670c8b5761ac3217","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:45:13.670Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Short answer: **the three tools are close, but not enough for a messy branch**. They let me fetch history once I already know what matters. They do not help me decide what matters.\n\nAs a receiving agent, my catch-up flow would be:\n\n1. `sessions branch <branch>`\n   I want to identify the likely canonical thread, recent resumes, review sessions, and subagents.\n\n2. Inspect the top 3-5 timelines:\n   Main session first, then any session marked as spawned from it, then review sessions with actionable outcomes.\n\n3. For timelines, skim turn summaries:\n   I‚Äôm looking for ‚Äúuser asked X‚Äù, ‚Äúagent changed Y‚Äù, ‚Äútests failed/passed‚Äù, ‚Äúblocked on Z‚Äù, ‚Äúreviewer requested A‚Äù.\n\n4. Pull records only for suspicious or decisive turns:\n   I do not want full transcript by default. I want exact records around commits, tool calls, failures, review comments, and user decisions.\n\nThe problem: `sessions` as proposed sounds like a list, but a catch-up agent needs a **triage surface**.\n\nMissing fields on `sessions`:\n\n- `session_key`\n- `branch`, `change`, `review`\n- `kind`: `main | subagent | review | resume | compaction | automation | unknown`\n- `parent_session_key`\n- `root_session_key`\n- `spawned_by_turn_key`\n- `created_at`, `updated_at`\n- `last_activity_at`\n- `actor/model/agent_name` if available\n- `status`: `active | completed | interrupted | failed | compacted | superseded`\n- `message_count` / `turn_count`\n- `tool_call_count`\n- `files_touched`\n- `commits_created`\n- `tests_run`\n- `has_user_messages`\n- `has_code_changes`\n- `has_errors`\n- `summary`\n- `last_user_intent`\n- `outcome`\n\nWithout those, sidecar noise is hard to filter. A subagent that searched docs, a review bot that only commented, and the main implementation thread may all look equivalent.\n\nI‚Äôd add affordances like:\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog sessions branch foo --tree\n```\n\nShow parent/child session structure. This is probably the single most important missing command.\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog sessions branch foo --main\n```\n\nReturn the likely canonical session. Use heuristics: root session, most user turns, code edits, commits, latest non-superseded activity.\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog sessions branch foo --interesting\n```\n\nHide obvious noise: tiny sessions, no user input, no changes, failed startup, pure browsing unless linked to a decision.\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog sessions branch foo --files crates/foo apps/bar\n```\n\nFind sessions relevant to files I‚Äôm about to touch.\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog timeline <session> --summary\n```\n\nGive turn-level summaries, not raw transcript shape.\n\nTimeline needs these per turn:\n\n- `turn_key`\n- timestamp\n- user request summary\n- assistant action summary\n- tools used\n- files touched\n- tests run/result\n- commits/staged changes\n- errors/blockers\n- spawned sessions\n- linked review comments\n- compaction/resume links\n- ‚Äúimportance‚Äù or ‚Äúdecision‚Äù marker\n\nRecords needs better slicing affordances:\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog records <session> --around-turn <turn> --context 3\nbut agentlog records <session> --kind user|assistant|tool|error|decision\nbut agentlog records <session> --grep \"panic\"\nbut agentlog records <session> --files crates/foo/src/lib.rs\n```\n\n`--from start|end|<index>` is too primitive. On a messy branch I rarely know the index. I know the file, error, commit, review comment, or approximate event.\n\nThe biggest missing concept is **lineage**. If there are compaction/resume sessions, I need the tool to say:\n\n> this session continues session A, which compacted session B; subagents C and D were spawned from turn T; review session E commented on commit X.\n\nSo I‚Äôd probably reshape the minimal set like this:\n\n1. `but agentlog sessions ... --tree --interesting`\n2. `but agentlog timeline <session-key> [--summary] [--with-children]`\n3. `but agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> [--around N | --kind K | --grep Q]`\n\nVerdict: **good skeleton, not enough for receiving-agent catch-up**. Add session classification, parent/root lineage, summaries, touched files/commits/tests, and filtering. Otherwise the agent burns time spelunking sidecar sessions instead of understanding the branch.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:45:13.670Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}